main event: Eleven persons in the Darlington-Wisconsin area sighted an unidentified aerial object on May 31, 1953. The object appeared as a steady white light coming from the east and disappearing to the west.
interesting points: The object appeared low on the eastern horizon, much brighter than the surrounding stars, and was reported to hover and then move in various directions with incredible speed, leaving no trail.
Police officers and a Green County Corps observer chased the object in their squad car at 70 mph but were unable to gain any ground on it.
The description of the object varied, with some observers stating it rose slowly while others said it appeared to suddenly dart across the sky.
Air Force personnel investigated the sighting and obtained azimuth and elevation readings from different observers at various locations in Darlington.
It was determined that the object's path closely paralleled the path of the planet Venus, leading investigators to conclude the object was likely Venus.
result: Unexplained, but likely the planet Venus
witnesses: Eleven persons, including police officers and a Green County Corps observer
